{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:17:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:17:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.23,0.27,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42893"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"7885"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43544"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of red, scaly patches on her face. The rash is photosensitive and mildly itchy.  She had eczema as a child but has not had any skin issues since the age of 6 years.  She feels otherwise well. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are erythematous, slightly raised, scaly plaques with minimal scarring across her cheeks and nose in a butterfly distribution. The rest of her skin examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral hydroxychloroquine","Oral prednisolone","Topical betamethasone","Oral doxycycline","Topical tacrolimus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cutaneous lupus erythematosus (CLE), specifically discoid lupus erythematosus (DLE) in a typical butterfly distribution. Cutaneous lupus erythematosus is a chronic autoimmune condition with no clear cause, and treatment is supportive of the flare-ups rather than curative.  The photosensitive nature, chronicity, and appearance of the rash are characteristic. DLE tends to heal without scarring.  In localised disease, topical therapy is the appropriate first-line treatment after general lifestyle changes.  Patients should be advised to avoid drying soaps, cease smoking, utilise sun protection and to avoid direct sunlight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical betamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment for localised CLE. Potent topical corticosteroids are effective in controlling inflammation and symptoms, particularly in early disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral hydroxychloroquine\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for cases that fail to respond to topical therapy, have widespread involvement, or show evidence of systemic disease. While effective, it requires baseline ophthalmological examination and regular monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical tacrolimus\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as a steroid-sparing agent in CLE, particularly for sensitive areas like the face. However, it is generally considered second-line topical therapy after topical corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for localised cutaneous disease without systemic involvement. Systemic corticosteroids are reserved for severe or systemic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for CLE. While it may have some anti-inflammatory properties, there is insufficient evidence to support its use as first-line therapy for CLE.  Oral doxyclycline can be used for acne treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical corticosteroids are first-line therapy for cutaneous lupus erythematosus.","Sun protection and smoking cessation are essential in managing cutaneous lupus erythematosus."],"references":["Gr\u00f6nhagen CM, Nyberg F. Cutaneous lupus erythematosus: An update. Indian Dermatol Online J. 2014 Jan;5(1):7-13. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3937495/","Saracino A. Cutaneous lupus erythematosus. The Australasian College of Dermatologists. 2024. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/cutaneous-lupus-erythematosus/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T14:06:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T14:07:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57434"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up